sp.l:
God morrow Ladies and fair troops of gallants, that have deposed the drowsy King of sleep, 
    to Crown our train with your rich presences, I salute you all;
Each one share thanks from thanks in general.

Would this case were my last, if I did not mark, nay all is one, 
    I have always a consort of Pipes about me, mine Ingle is all fire and water; 
    I marked, by this Candle (which is none of Gods Angels) I remember, you started back at sprite and flame.

Sir Adam, an Ape? there is no more reason in an Ape, than in a very plain Monkey; 
    for an Ape has no tail, but we all know, or it is our duty to know, love has two tails; 
    In my judgement, if love be a beast, that beast is a bunce of Reddis; for a bunce of Reddis is wise meat without Mutton, and so is love.

It is well Sir, I have strength to bear yours methinks; 
    fore God you are grown a piece of a Critic, since you fell into my hands: 
ah little rogue, your wit has picked up her crumbs pretty and well.

Master Horace, your inventions do her no good in the universalities; 
    yet here is two shillings for your 
wits; nay by Jesu you shall take it if it were more: yonder bald Adams, is put my nose from his joint; 
but Adam I will be even to you: this is my cogitations, I will indite the Ladies and 
    Miniuer caps to a dinner of Plums, and I shall desire you M. Horace, to speak or rail; you can rail 
    I hope in God all mighty.

 
The King, gods Lord, I do forget the King; 
Widow, think on my words, I must be gone 
To wait his rising, I will return anon.

The same M. Horace, he that has but a remnant or parcel of hair, his crown is clipped and pared away; 
methinks it is an excellent quality to be bald; 
    for if there stuck a nose and two eyes in his pate, he might wear two faces under one hood.

What, dost summon a parley my little Drumstick? it is too late; 
    thou seest my red flag is hung out, I will fill 
thy guts with thine own carrion carcass, and then eat them up instead of Sausages.

By Jesu, it is best you give good words too, lest I beat out your tongue, 
    and make your word never to be taken more; 
    do you hear, five pounds, five pounds Tucky.

 
Dare defend baldness, which our conquering Muse 
Has beaten down so flat? Well, we will go, 
And see what weapons their weak wits do bring; 
If sharpe, we will spread a large and nobler wing; 
Tucca, here lies thy Peace: war roars again; 
My Sword shall never cut thee, but my pen.

 
How now? be well good Horace, here is no wound; 

  You are slain by your own fears; how dost thou man? 
Come, put thy heart into his place again; 
Thy outside is neither pierced, nor inside slain.

Two words Horace about your ears: how chance it passes, that you bid Good-bye to an honest trade 
of building Chimneys, and laying down Bricks, for a worse handicraftness to make nothing but raises; 
your Muse leans upon nothing but filthy rotten tails, such as stand on Poules head, how chance?

Thou art the true arraigned Poet, and shouldst have been hanged, but for one of these part-takers, these charitable 
Copper-laced Christians, that fetched thee out of Purgatory, (Players I mean) Theaterians pouch-mouth Stage-walkers; 
for this Poet, for this, thou must lie with these four wenches, in that blanket, for this ---

 
Must I then go? it is easy to say no, 
Must is the King himself, and I must go; 
Shall I then go? that word is thine; I shall, 
Is thy command: I go because I shall; 
Will I then go? I ask myself; o ill, 
King, says I must; you, I shall; Aye, I will.

 
I had a constant wife, I will tell the King; 
Until the King --- what dost thou smile? art thou 
A Father?

 
Do not confound me quite; for mine own guilt, 
Speaks more within me than thy tongue contains; 
Thy sorrow is my shame: yet herein springs, 
Joy out of sorrow, boldness out of of shame; 
For I by this have found, once in my life, 
A faithful subject, thou a constant wife.
